  <!-- DESIGN LAWS -->
  <section class="laws" id="laws" aria-labelledby="laws-title">
    <p class="section-tag">Design laws</p>
    <h2 class="laws-title" id="laws-title">What impeccable refuses to ship.</h2>
    <p class="laws-intro">
      Bad patterns have names. Naming them is the first step to banning them. These are the patterns impeccable catches before they make it to production.
    </p>

    <div class="laws-grid">
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">01</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">Side-stripe borders</h3>
        <p class="law-body">The colored left-border on cards and callouts as a hierarchy signal. It's shorthand for design thinking. Rewritten with full borders, background tints, leading numbers, or nothing at all.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">02</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">Gradient text</h3>
        <p class="law-body">Background-clip text with a gradient fill. Decorative without meaning, and a clear AI tell. Replaced with a single solid color. Emphasis comes from weight and scale, not chrome.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">03</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">The hero-metric template</h3>
        <p class="law-body">Big number, small label, supporting stats, gradient accent. A SaaS landing page pattern so overused it stopped communicating anything years ago. Rewritten from scratch.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">04</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">Identical card grids</h3>
        <p class="law-body">Icon + heading + text, same card size, repeated until the grid fills. Cards are the lazy answer. There are always better affordances when the content is actually considered.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">05</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">Glassmorphism by reflex</h3>
        <p class="law-body">Blur and glass used decoratively because it "looks modern." When everything is glass, nothing is. Used sparingly and purposefully, or not at all.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="law">
        <div class="law-num">06</div>
        <h3 class="law-title-text">Theme chosen by category</h3>
        <p class="law-body">Dark because "developer tools look cool dark." Light because "safer." Theme is decided by a physical scene sentence: who uses this, where, under what ambient light, in what mood. Not a reflex.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

